%T A393796 110703193,565172681,2912662332,15134815143,79217763042,417322670366,
%U A393796 2211189886587,11776843602465,63017459449705,338635023576204,1826738858413996,9888944699840202
%N A393796 a(n) is the number of different ways to move from A to B along grid paths in an equilateral triangular grid ABC of side n units such that the distance between A and each successive point of the path increases.
%C A393796 An equilateral triangular grid of side 3 units:
%C A393796         .
%C A393796        / \
%C A393796       .---.
%C A393796      / \ / \
%C A393796     .---.---.
%C A393796    / \ / \ / \
%C A393796   .---.---.---.
%C A393796 Let ABC be an equilateral triangular grid of side n containing n^2 unit equilateral triangles. The x axis is defined along AB and the y axis is defined along AC such that starting point A has coordinates (0,0), finishing point B has coordinates (n,0) and C is at (0,n).
%C A393796 A grid point (x,y) on a path of the moving point P satisfies the following conditions when generating string of coordinates of grid points on a valid path: x + y <= n, y <= n/2, and x^2 + y^2 + x*y should increase when moving to the next grid point.
%H A393796 Janaka Rodrigo, <a href="/A393796/a393796.txt">Python Code for sets of string of coordinates of grid points</a>
%H A393796 Janaka Rodrigo, <a href="/A393796/a393796.pdf">Illustration of grid paths for n=3</a>
%H A393796 Janaka Rodrigo, <a href="/A393796/a393796_1.pdf">Manual Counting of Valid Grid Paths for n = 4</a>
%F A393796 a(n) = T(n,0) where T(0,0) = 1 and T(x,y) = [x>0] * T(x-1,y) + [y>0] * T(x,y-1) + [x>0 and y<x-1] * T(x-1,y+1) where [] is the Iverson bracket. - _Sean A. Irvine_, Mar 08 2026
%e A393796 n = 2 has 3 distinct sets of strings of coordinates:
%e A393796  {(0,0), (1,0), (2,0)},
%e A393796  {(0,0), (0,1), (1,1), (2,0)},
%e A393796  {(0,0), (1,0), (1,1), (2,0)}.
%e A393796 Therefore a(2) = 3.
%Y A393796 Cf. A112675, A266513, A288148.
